Adaptive Cryptographic State Machines: A Formal Framework for Quantum-Safe Decentralized Ledgers

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

The imminent arrival of cryptographically relevant quantum computers (CRQCs) threatens all deployed blockchains that rely on the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem (ECDLP) over secp256k1. Recent circuit optimizations (Google Quantum AI, 2026) demonstrate that a CRQC with as few as 1200 logical qubits can solve secp256k1 ECDLP in under 23 minutes—approximately 9 minutes in an on‑spend primed attack, comparable to Bitcoin’s block interval. Despite this, decentralized ledgers exhibit a critical adaptation gap: the coordination time T_C required to upgrade cryptographic primitives (12–20 months) may exceed the remaining time until quantum break. We formalize this gap via a threshold public goods game and prove an Adaptation Gap Theorem: under rational validator behavior, the probability of successful voluntary pre‑quantum migration decays exponentially as \exp(-\Omega(N(1-\theta)^2)), rendering it negligible for large validator sets.

To solve the adaptation gap, we transition from voluntary coordination to systemic enforcement via the Adaptive Cryptographic State Machine (ACSM). The ACSM implements three mathematically proven pillars:

1. Protocol‑Level Forcing Function: A degrading reward coefficient \phi(t) penalizes non‑agile validators, transforming the upgrade decision from a coordination game into a set of independent rational choices by making a_i = 1 strictly dominant for all t > t^*.
2. Hybrid Commitment State: A composite address \alpha = H(H(\text{pk}_{\text{EC}}) \| H(\text{pk}_{\text{PQC}})) supports existential unforgeability: breaking both classical and post‑quantum primitives is necessary to forge a transition.
3. Zero‑Knowledge Key Migration: A NIZK proof of the migration relation enables dark account migration without leaking \text{pk}_{\text{old}}, with quantum soundness proven under lattice assumptions; a nullifier prevents double migration.

We further provide a recursive SNARK aggregation lemma showing that the 33\times signature size increase can be amortized to constant verification time, ensuring liveness. The ACSM is proved safe (inconsistent state probability \leq 2^{-128}) and live (O(\text{block time} \cdot \log N)) under honest majority. All results are purely mathematical; no empirical simulations are included.

