1.6 Related Work

Our work builds on several threads: Shor’s algorithm optimizations for ECDLP (Gidney & Ekerå, 2021; Google Quantum AI, 2026); NIST post‑quantum standards (FIPS 203–206); QROM security reductions (Albrecht et al., 2022; Don et al., 2022); coordination game analyses of blockchain upgrades (Barrera & Hurder, 2024); and cryptographic agility proposals (Boneh et al., 2023). The forcing function draws inspiration from Ethereum’s inactivity leak and from economic penalty mechanisms in proof‑of‑stake systems. The hybrid address concept extends discussions on hash‑committed accounts (Ethereum Community, 2026). The ZK migration approach parallels privacy‑preserving nullifier systems (Semaphore, Zenrock Hush) but adapts them to post‑quantum assumptions. Recursive SNARK aggregation for PQC signatures is enabled by recent lattice‑based folding schemes (LatticeFold+, Boneh & Chen, 2025).

1.7 Scope and Limitations

This work is theoretical. We do not provide implementation code, empirical benchmarks, or simulations. We assume standard cryptographic hardness assumptions (ECDLP, MLWE, collision resistance of hash functions, soundness of NIZK). We assume an honest majority (>2/3 stake) for consensus safety and liveness. The forcing function parameters (\phi(t), \rho) are assumed to be set by governance; we do not model optimal parameter selection. The recursive SNARK aggregation lemma assumes the existence of a post‑quantum IVC scheme (e.g., LatticeFold) and does not prove its security from first principles.

Despite these limitations, the formal framework provides a rigorous foundation for future implementation, simulation, and standardization efforts. The adaptation gap theorem and the three pillars together constitute a complete mathematical solution to the quantum threat in decentralized ledgers.

Chapter 2: Formal Problem Statement & Mathematical Preliminaries

2.1 Blockchain State Machine Model

We model a decentralized ledger as a deterministic state machine:

\mathcal{L} = (S, \mathcal{T}, \mathcal{V}, \delta)

where:

· S \in \{0,1\}^* is the global state, representing UTXO sets, account balances, smart contract storage, and consensus metadata.
· \mathcal{T} is the set of all possible transactions.
· \mathcal{V} is the verification rule set, containing a family of polynomial-time algorithms (\text{KeyGen}, \text{Sign}, \text{Verify}) for one or more signature schemes.
· \delta: S \times \mathcal{T} \to S \cup \{\bot\} is the deterministic state transition function, satisfying:

\delta(s, tx) = \begin{cases}
s' \in S, & \text{if } tx \text{ is valid under } \mathcal{V} \text{ and applicable},\\
\bot, & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}

A blockchain is a sequence of blocks B_1, B_2, \ldots where each block contains an ordered list of transactions. Consensus ensures that all honest nodes agree on the same sequence. Two critical properties must hold under honest majority:

· Safety: No two honest nodes ever disagree on the confirmed transaction order.
· Liveness: Transactions eventually get confirmed by every honest node.

2.2 Cryptographic Primitives in Current Deployments

Most deployed blockchains (Bitcoin, Ethereum, and their derivatives) rely on the Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (ECDSA) over the curve secp256k1, defined by the equation y^2 = x^3 + 7 over the prime field \mathbb{F}_p with

p = 2^{256} - 2^{32} - 977.

The group order is a 256-bit prime n. Security rests on the hardness of the Elliptic Curve Discrete Logarithm Problem (ECDLP): given points P, Q on the curve with Q = [k]P, find integer k \in [0, n-1].

Definition 2.1 (ECDLP advantage). For a probabilistic algorithm \mathcal{A},

\text{Adv}^{\text{ECDLP}}_{\mathcal{A}} = \Pr\left[\mathcal{A}(P, Q) = k \mid Q = [k]P,\ k \stackrel{\$}{\leftarrow} \mathbb{Z}_n\right].

We say ECDLP is (t, \epsilon)-hard if no algorithm running in time t has advantage greater than \epsilon.

Classically, the best known algorithms for secp256k1 run in time O(\sqrt{n}) \approx 2^{128} (Pollard rho), which is considered infeasible.

2.3 Quantum Vulnerability Condition

Let \text{QC} denote a cryptographically relevant quantum computer (CRQC) capable of running Shor's algorithm on instances of size n=256. Define:

· T_Q: the time required for such a QC to solve a single ECDLP instance, including circuit execution, error correction overhead, and readout.
· T_C: the minimal time required for the blockchain's governance to coordinate and activate an upgrade from the current verification rules \mathcal{V} to a post‑quantum rule set \mathcal{V}'.

Definition 2.2 (Quantum vulnerability). The blockchain \mathcal{L} is quantum vulnerable if there exists a CRQC such that T_Q \ll T_C and an adversary can, upon obtaining a public key, forge a signature before the chain can react.

Harvest‑now‑decrypt‑later (HNDL). An adversary can record all public keys that ever appear on chain (or are broadcast in the mempool) and store them. At time \tau_Q when a CRQC becomes available, the adversary breaks all recorded keys in parallel (or sequentially with total time T_Q per key). This decouples the attack time from the present day. As noted by Chaincode Labs, 20% to 50% of all bitcoins in circulation (4–10 million BTC) are potentially vulnerable to attacks using CRQCs. Exchange addresses holding hundreds of thousands of bitcoins are priority targets.

2.4 Thesis Formalization

We define Ownership Collapse as the event that an adversary, using a CRQC, can forge a valid signature for any unspent output or account that has ever exposed its public key on chain, with probability at least 1 - \text{negl}(\lambda).

Thesis. For any blockchain \mathcal{L} that relies on ECDLP hardness and has upgrade coordination time T_C,

\lim_{T_C / T_Q \to \infty} \Pr[\text{Ownership Collapse} \mid \text{CRQC arrival}] = 1,

while the probability of consensus failure (e.g., fork) remains negligible under honest majority.

The ratio T_C / T_Q captures the adaptation gap. When coordination is much slower than attack, collapse is inevitable.

2.5 Notation

Throughout this work:

· \lambda denotes the security parameter (e.g., \lambda = 128).
· \text{negl}(\lambda) denotes a negligible function: f(\lambda) = O(2^{-\omega(\log \lambda)}).
· \Pr[\cdot] denotes probability over random coin flips of algorithms and any implicit randomness.
· \mathbb{E}[\cdot] denotes expectation.
· N: number of validators (or miners) in the consensus protocol.
· \theta \in (0.5, 1]: upgrade threshold (commonly \theta = 2/3).
· \tau_Q: random variable representing the arrival time of a CRQC (years from 2025).

