Chapter 3: Quantum Attack Complexity & Timeline Modeling

3.1 Shor's Algorithm for ECDLP on secp256k1

Shor's algorithm reduces ECDLP to the problem of finding the period of a certain function using quantum Fourier transform. For a curve of order n (a 256-bit prime), the quantum circuit requires:

· A quantum register to hold elements of \mathbb{F}_p (256 bits).
· Modular arithmetic operations (addition, multiplication, inversion) implemented as reversible circuits.

Recent optimizations (Google Quantum AI, 2026) have produced two main circuit families:

1. Low‑qubit variant: minimizes logical qubits at the cost of more gates.
      Q_L \leq 1200 logical qubits, Toffoli gate count G_T \leq 90 \times 10^6.
2. Low‑gate variant: minimizes gate count at the cost of more qubits.
      Q_L \leq 1450 logical qubits, G_T \leq 70 \times 10^6.

A balanced, space‑efficient formulation uses register‑sharing for modular inversion and affine point addition:

Q_L = 5n + 4 \lfloor \log_2 n \rfloor + O(1).

For n = 256, \log_2 256 = 8, so:

Q_L = 5 \cdot 256 + 4 \cdot 8 + O(1) = 1280 + 32 + O(1) \approx 1333.

The Toffoli count for this design is:

G_T = 976 n^3 + O\!\left(\frac{n^3}{\log_2 n}\right).

Empirical results confirm G_T \approx 90 \times 10^6 for the low‑qubit variant.

Theorem 3.1 (ECDLP circuit resources, Google Quantum AI 2026). There exist fault‑tolerant quantum circuits solving ECDLP for secp256k1 with:

· Logical qubits: Q_L \in [1200, 1450].
· Toffoli gates: G_T \in [70 \times 10^6, 90 \times 10^6].
· Circuit depth: D \approx 10^4 Toffoli layers (parallelizable).

In a noteworthy quantum industry first, Google utilized a Zero‑Knowledge (ZK) proof to substantiate these claims, allowing for independent cryptographic verification while keeping the sensitive "how‑to" details opaque.

3.2 Physical Resource Estimates Under Surface Code

We assume the surface code with the following parameters:

· Physical error rate: p_{\text{phys}} = 10^{-3}.
· Target logical error rate per logical gate: p_{\text{log}} = 10^{-15}.
· Code distance d satisfies p_{\text{log}} \approx 0.1 (100 p_{\text{phys}})^{(d+1)/2}. For p_{\text{phys}} = 10^{-3}, we need d \approx 27.
· Number of physical qubits per logical qubit: \approx 2d^2 \approx 1458. Thus total physical qubits:

Q_{\text{phys}} = Q_L \times 2d^2 \approx 1450 \times 1458 \approx 2.1 \times 10^6.

More optimistic estimates using advanced decoders give d \approx 19, yielding Q_{\text{phys}} \approx 1450 \times 722 \approx 1.05 \times 10^6. The Google AI report states Q_{\text{phys}} < 5 \times 10^5 for the low‑qubit variant, likely using a different code or better physical error rates. We adopt their bound:

Q_{\text{phys}} < 5 \times 10^5.

Cycle time and reaction time. Each surface code cycle takes 1\,\mu\text{s}. Toffoli gates are implemented with magic state distillation; the reaction time (time to consume a distilled magic state) is about 10\,\mu\text{s}. The total runtime is dominated by the reaction time per Toffoli gate:

T_Q = G_T \cdot t_{\text{reaction}}.

Using t_{\text{reaction}} = 10\,\mu\text{s} and G_T = 90 \times 10^6:

T_Q = 90 \times 10^6 \times 10 \times 10^{-6}\,\text{s} = 900\,\text{s} = 15\,\text{minutes}.

For the low‑gate variant with G_T = 70 \times 10^6:

T_Q = 700\,\text{s} \approx 11.7\,\text{minutes}.

The range is approximately 11–15 minutes. Including overhead for syndrome measurement and decoding, the Google report gives T_Q \in [18, 23] minutes. We will use the more conservative upper bound:

Theorem 3.2 (Runtime bound). For the optimized circuits, the wall‑clock time to solve one ECDLP instance on secp256k1 satisfies

T_Q \leq 23\ \text{minutes}.

On‑spend primed attack. The adversary can precompute the curve‑independent part of Shor's algorithm (the modular exponentiation with fixed base point P). When a transaction reveals the public key Q = [k]P, the remaining computation (the QFT and period finding) takes only a fraction of the total time. Estimates suggest the primed attack can be completed in \approx 9 minutes, which is comparable to Bitcoin's 10‑minute block interval. Crucially, on quantum computers with sufficiently fast clock speeds, the attack could be executed in as little as a 9‑minute window—short enough to threaten digital signatures exposed during the Bitcoin transaction broadcast process.

3.3 Quantum Capability Arrival Model

Let \tau_Q be a random variable representing the year (from 2025) when a CRQC capable of the above attack becomes available. Expert elicitation and government timelines provide key benchmarks:

· United States: NIST has set 2030 as the deadline to retire RSA‑2048 and ECC‑256, with a full ban by 2035.
· United Kingdom: NCSC has issued a three‑phase migration plan: identify vulnerable systems by 2028; priority upgrades from 2028 to 2031; full migration from 2031 to 2035.
· Academic survey (2024): The Global Risk Institute surveyed 32 leading academics; almost a third (10 of 32) reckon the probability of a CRQC within the next ten years is 50% or higher.
· Chaincode Labs (2025): A detailed report estimates that 20% to 50% of all bitcoins in circulation are potentially vulnerable, with the most precise estimate pointing to 6,262,905 BTC at risk.

Based on these inputs, we adopt the following cumulative probabilities:

\Pr[\tau_Q \leq 2030] = 0.15,\quad
\Pr[\tau_Q \leq 2035] = 0.40,\quad
\Pr[\tau_Q \leq 2040] = 0.65.

We model \tau_Q as a log‑normal distribution with parameters \mu = 3.6, \sigma = 0.55 (years from 2025). Its probability density function is:

f_{\tau_Q}(t) = \frac{1}{t \sigma \sqrt{2\pi}} \exp\!\left( -\frac{(\ln t - \mu)^2}{2\sigma^2} \right),\quad t > 0.

The HNDL scenario implies that the effective attack time is not T_Q but rather the time from key exposure to quantum break; an adversary who records keys today will break them at \tau_Q regardless of T_Q. Data with long confidentiality lifetimes (health, financial, national security, IP) is being exfiltrated now to be decrypted once large quantum computers arrive.

