Appendix A: Cryptographic Primitives & Mathematical Background

A.1 Elliptic Curve Cryptography

Definition A.1 (Elliptic curve over finite field). Let \mathbb{F}_p be a finite field with prime p > 3. An elliptic curve E over \mathbb{F}_p is defined by the Weierstrass equation

E: y^2 = x^3 + ax + b, \quad a,b \in \mathbb{F}_p,\ 4a^3 + 27b^2 \neq 0.

The set E(\mathbb{F}_p) consists of all points (x,y) \in \mathbb{F}_p^2 satisfying the equation together with a point at infinity \mathcal{O}. This set forms an abelian group under the chord‑tangent law.

Definition A.2 (secp256k1). The curve secp256k1 is defined by a = 0, b = 7 over the prime field

p = 2^{256} - 2^{32} - 977.

Its group order is the prime

n = 115792089237316195423570985008687907852837564279074904382605163141518161494337.

Definition A.3 (ECDLP). Given P \in E(\mathbb{F}_p) of prime order n and Q = [k]P (scalar multiplication), the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem is to find k \in \mathbb{Z}_n. The advantage of an adversary \mathcal{A} is

\text{Adv}^{\text{ECDLP}}_{\mathcal{A}} = \Pr[\mathcal{A}(P,Q) = k].

A.2 Hash Functions

Definition A.4 (Collision resistance). A hash function H: \{0,1\}^* \to \{0,1\}^\ell is collision‑resistant if for any probabilistic polynomial‑time adversary \mathcal{A},

\Pr[(x,y) \leftarrow \mathcal{A}(1^\lambda) : x \neq y,\ H(x)=H(y)] \leq \text{negl}(\lambda).

Definition A.5 (Quantum collision resistance). In the quantum setting, the adversary can query H in superposition. The bound becomes

\Pr[\text{collision}] \leq O\left(\frac{2^{\ell/2}}{T}\right)

for an adversary making T quantum queries (Grover’s search for collisions).

A.3 Digital Signatures

Definition A.6 (EUF‑CMA security). A signature scheme \Sigma = (\text{KeyGen}, \text{Sign}, \text{Verify}) is existentially unforgeable under chosen message attacks if for any PPT adversary \mathcal{A} with access to a signing oracle \text{Sign}(sk, \cdot),

\Pr\left[ \begin{array}{l}
(pk,sk) \leftarrow \text{KeyGen}(1^\lambda),\\
(m^*, \sigma^*) \leftarrow \mathcal{A}^{\text{Sign}(sk,\cdot)}(pk) :\\
\text{Verify}(pk, m^*, \sigma^*) = 1 \land m^* \notin Q
\end{array} \right] \leq \text{negl}(\lambda),

where Q is the set of messages queried to the signing oracle.

