Appendix B: Quantum Algorithms for ECDLP

B.1 Shor’s Algorithm – High‑Level Description

Shor’s algorithm reduces ECDLP to period finding. For a point P of order n, define the function f(k) = [k]P. The period of f is exactly n. Using a quantum Fourier transform, one can find n efficiently.

Algorithm B.1 (Shor for ECDLP).

1. Prepare two quantum registers: first register of size 2m qubits (where m = \lceil \log_2 n \rceil), second register to hold a curve point.
2. Initialize first register to uniform superposition: \frac{1}{\sqrt{2^{2m}}}\sum_{a=0}^{2^{2m}-1}|a\rangle|0\rangle.
3. Compute f(a) = [a]P into the second register: \frac{1}{\sqrt{2^{2m}}}\sum_{a=0}^{2^{2m}-1}|a\rangle|[a]P\rangle.
4. Apply Quantum Fourier Transform to the first register.
5. Measure the first register. With high probability, the measured value yields information about the period.
6. Repeat to obtain enough samples and use continued fractions to recover n.

B.2 Modular Arithmetic Circuits

The critical resource for Shor’s algorithm is the modular arithmetic. For a modulus N (here the curve order n), modular exponentiation is implemented via repeated squaring. The circuit uses controlled addition and multiplication.

Lemma B.1 (Modular multiplication cost). Using the Schönhage‑Strassen algorithm, multiplication of two n-bit numbers costs O(n \log n \log \log n) Toffoli gates. For n=256, this constant is small; optimized circuits use Karatsuba and Toom‑Cook.

Lemma B.2 (ECDLP circuit depth). The depth of the modular exponentiation circuit for a 256‑bit exponent is O(n \log n). With parallelization, the depth can be reduced to O(n).

B.3 Surface Code Overhead

The surface code encodes logical qubits into physical qubits arranged in a 2D lattice. The code distance d determines error correction capability.

Theorem B.3 (Surface code threshold). For the depolarizing channel with physical error rate p_{\text{phys}}, there exists a threshold p_{\text{th}} \approx 0.01. For p_{\text{phys}} < p_{\text{th}}, increasing d reduces logical error rate as

p_{\text{log}} \approx c (p_{\text{phys}}/p_{\text{th}})^{(d+1)/2}.

For p_{\text{phys}} = 10^{-3} and p_{\text{log}} = 10^{-15}, we solve for d:

10^{-15} \approx 0.1 \cdot (100 \cdot 10^{-3})^{(d+1)/2} = 0.1 \cdot (0.1)^{(d+1)/2}.

Thus (0.1)^{(d+1)/2} = 10^{-14}, taking logs: -(d+1)/2 = -14 → d+1 = 28 → d = 27.

The number of physical qubits per logical qubit is approximately 2d^2 = 1458. For Q_L = 1450, Q_{\text{phys}} \approx 2.1 \times 10^6. However, using better decoders (e.g., belief propagation with ordered statistics) can reduce the required distance to d \approx 19, giving Q_{\text{phys}} \approx 5 \times 10^5.

