Appendix C: Security Reduction Proofs

C.1 Forking Lemma for Classical Signatures

Lemma C.1 (General forking lemma, Pointcheval & Stern). Let \mathcal{A} be a probabilistic polynomial‑time algorithm that, on input a public key pk, produces a valid forgery (m, \sigma = (h, \mathbf{z})) for a signature scheme of the Fiat‑Shamir type, making at most q_H random oracle queries. Then there exists an algorithm \mathcal{B} that, by running \mathcal{A} twice with different random oracle responses, can extract a solution to the underlying hard problem with probability at least

\epsilon_{\mathcal{B}} \geq \frac{\epsilon_{\mathcal{A}}^2}{q_H} - \frac{1}{2^\ell},

where \ell is the length of the challenge.

C.2 QROM Reduction for ML‑DSA (Sketch)

Theorem C.2 (Simplified QROM reduction). Let \mathcal{A} be a quantum adversary against the EUF‑CMA security of ML‑DSA making at most Q superposition queries to the random oracle H and at most S signing queries. Then there exists a quantum adversary \mathcal{B} against Module‑LWE such that

\text{Adv}^{\text{MLWE}}_{\mathcal{B}} \geq \frac{\epsilon^2}{8 Q^3 S} - \text{negl}.

Proof idea. The reduction uses the one‑way to hiding (O2H) lemma. The adversary’s superposition queries are replaced by a simulated oracle that programs responses on a set of inputs T. The size of T is bounded by O(Q^2). By measuring a query in the computational basis, the reduction extracts two distinct inputs with probability \Omega(\epsilon^2 / Q^3). Then the classical forking lemma applies. The signing queries are handled via the standard abort technique from the classical reduction. ∎

C.3 Hybrid Signature Security

Theorem C.3 (Hybrid EUF‑CMA). Let \Sigma_1, \Sigma_2 be EUF‑CMA secure. Define \Sigma_{\text{hyb}} with \text{KeyGen}_{\text{hyb}} = (\text{KeyGen}_1, \text{KeyGen}_2), \text{Sign}_{\text{hyb}}(sk_1,sk_2,m) = (\text{Sign}_1(sk_1,m), \text{Sign}_2(sk_2,m)), and \text{Verify}_{\text{hyb}}(pk_1,pk_2,m,(\sigma_1,\sigma_2)) = \text{Verify}_1(pk_1,m,\sigma_1) \lor \text{Verify}_2(pk_2,m,\sigma_2). Then \Sigma_{\text{hyb}} is EUF‑CMA secure with advantage

\text{Adv}_{\Sigma_{\text{hyb}}}(\mathcal{A}) \leq \text{Adv}_{\Sigma_1}(\mathcal{B}_1) + \text{Adv}_{\Sigma_2}(\mathcal{B}_2).

Proof. Consider the following sequence of games:

· Game 0: The real hybrid game.
· Game 1: Replace \text{Sign}_2 with a simulator that outputs random signatures (using the fact that \Sigma_2 is EUF‑CMA, the adversary cannot distinguish).
· Game 2: Replace \text{Verify}_2 to always return 0. This reduces to \Sigma_1 alone.

The advantage difference between games is bounded by the advantage against \Sigma_2. Similarly, symmetry gives the other bound. ∎

