Appendix D: Game Theory & Large Deviations

D.1 Hoeffding’s Inequality

Theorem D.1 (Hoeffding). Let X_1, \dots, X_N be independent random variables with a_i \leq X_i \leq b_i. Let S_N = \sum_{i=1}^N X_i and \mu = \mathbb{E}[S_N]. Then for any t > 0,

\Pr[S_N - \mu \geq t] \leq \exp\left(-\frac{2t^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N (b_i - a_i)^2}\right).

For Bernoulli variables X_i \in \{0,1\}, we have b_i - a_i = 1, so

\Pr\left(\frac{S_N}{N} \geq p + \delta\right) \leq \exp(-2N\delta^2).

D.2 Equilibrium Computation for Threshold Game

Lemma D.2 (Mixed equilibrium condition). In the threshold public goods game with symmetric players, a mixed strategy equilibrium satisfies

p = F_C\left( \mathbb{E}[B] \cdot \sum_{k=\lceil \theta N-1\rceil}^{N-1} \binom{N-1}{k} p^k (1-p)^{N-1-k} \right).

Proof. The expected payoff for playing a_i=1 is \mathbb{E}[B] P_{\text{succ}}(p) - c_i. For the marginal player with cost c, we set this to zero, giving c = \mathbb{E}[B] P_{\text{succ}}(p). The fraction of players with cost \leq c is F_C(c). Hence p = F_C(\mathbb{E}[B] P_{\text{succ}}(p)). ∎

D.3 Adaptation Gap Bound Derivation

Assume \mathbb{E}[B] \to 0, then p \to 0. For any \epsilon > 0, for sufficiently small \mathbb{E}[B], we have p \leq \epsilon. The probability of reaching threshold \theta is

\Pr[\text{Bin}(N,p) \geq \theta N] \leq \exp(-2N(\theta - \epsilon)^2) \quad \text{for } \theta > \epsilon.

Take \epsilon = \theta/2 (valid when \theta > 0). Then

\Pr[\text{success}] \leq \exp(-2N(\theta/2)^2) = \exp\left(-\frac{N\theta^2}{2}\right).

For \theta = 2/3, this is \exp(-2N/9).

