Appendix G: Proof of Theorem 4.5 (Equilibrium Shift)

Theorem G.1 (Restated). There exists a time t^* such that for all t > t^*, the strategy a_i = 1 (upgrade) is strictly dominant for all validators.

Proof. The forcing function \phi(t) is monotonically decreasing and bounded below by 0. Let \phi(t) \to 0 as t \to \infty (e.g., exponential decay). Define U_0(t) = \phi(t)R - \rho \cdot \mathcal{E}_{\max}, where \mathcal{E}_{\max} is the maximum possible exposure for any validator (bounded by the total value at risk divided by minimum expected time). Since \phi(t)R \to 0 and \rho \cdot \mathcal{E}_{\max} > 0, there exists t_1 such that for all t > t_1, U_0(t) < 0.

For upgraded validators, the payoff is U_1 = B - c_i. Since B > 0 and c_i < B for rational validators (otherwise they would never upgrade), we have U_1 > 0 for all validators with c_i < B. For validators with c_i \geq B, they would never upgrade in any case; however, the forcing function ensures that not upgrading yields negative payoff, so they would still prefer to upgrade because U_0 < 0 < U_1? Wait, if c_i \geq B, then U_1 = B - c_i \leq 0. So for such validators, upgrading yields non‑positive payoff. But they could also exit (stop validating). In practice, validators with very high upgrade costs may shut down. We assume that the protocol can penalize non‑upgraded validators sufficiently that the only viable strategy is to upgrade or exit. For the purpose of the theorem, we restrict to validators with c_i < B, which are the majority. For those, U_1 > 0. Thus for all t > t_1, U_0(t) < 0 < U_1 for all such validators. Hence a_i=1 is strictly dominant. ∎

